		<div class="postarea">

			            
            <div class="posttitle">		

				<h3>The 11 Ultimate Rules of Chili</h3>

                    <div class="postauthor">            
                        <p>Posted by <a href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/author/andrewdc/" title="Posts by Andrew Del-Colle">Andrew Del-Colle</a> on Thursday, February 3, 2011 &middot; <a href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili/2011/02/03/#comments">9 Comments</a>&nbsp;</p>
                    </div>
                    
            </div>

			<iframe src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http%3A%2F%2Fblogs.menshealth.com%2Fguy-gourmet%2Fthe-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili%2F2011%2F02%2F03%2F&amp;layout=standard&amp;show_faces=true&amp;width=450&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" allowTransparency="true" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width:450px;height:25px;margin-top:5px;"></iframe><p><a rel="attachment wp-att-1628" href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili/2011/02/03/headerchiliexperiment-2/"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1628" title="HeaderChiliExperiment" src="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/files/2011/02/HeaderChiliExperiment.jpg" alt="" width="620" height="380" /></a><br />
Whoever first said the eyes are the window to the soul was wrong. Sorry, but that lofty title belongs to chili. From the choice of the meat to the level of heat, you can tell a lot about who a person really is by what goes into their chili.</p>
<p>And it&#8217;s because of this that we here at Guy Gourmet were so intrigued by  the first annual <a href="http://chilifest2011.com/" target="_blank">New York Chili Festival</a> held January 30 at Chelsea Market. What happens when you take 24 teams from some of the best restaurants and gastropubs in the city, give each team some dry-aged, locally-raised beef , and then let them loose to create some mind-blowing chili? A whole lot of soul bearing, that&#8217;s what. From tasty tomatillo- and mole-based chilies to heartier, more traditional styles,  the market&#8217;s concourse was an extravaganza of flavors and textures.</p>
<p>At the end of the night, it was <a href="http://www.northernspyfoodco.com/" target="_blank">Northern Spy Food Co.</a> that took home the 2011 Golden Chili Mug. but with so much chili knowledge in one location, we couldn&#8217;t leave without asking participants for a few of their ultimate chili rules. We boiled down their responses and came up with what can only be described as the ultimate guide to making chili. Bust these tips out for the Super Bowl or the next time you make a batch for yourself and we guarantee you&#8217;ll wind up with a big pot of deliciousness.  (And for more great Super Bowl recommendations, check out <a href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/chef-skill-the-5-commandments-of-the-ultimate-sandwich-according-to-tyler-florence/2010/10/07/">The 5 Commandments of the Ultimate Sandwich</a> and <a href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-spiciest-super-bowl-snack/2011/01/25/" target="_blank">The Spiciest Super Bowl Snack</a>.)</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 1</strong><br />
<em>It&#8217;s gotta have chilies. Sometimes people forget that. </em><br />
—Ben Ibarra, Sueños</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 2</strong><br />
<em>Go to a Spanish-American grocery store and get some nice dried chilies. You can use the crappiest beef ever, but if you get good chilies from a Mexican bodega, you can turn that beef into some great flavors.</em><br />
—Noah Bernamoff, Mile End</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 3</strong><br />
<em>When you think there&#8217;s enough chili powder, it needs more.</em><br />
—Yvon de Tassigny, Fette Sau</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 4</strong><br />
<em>Don&#8217;t be a CHUMP&#8211;eat some hot chili. Eating chili that&#8217;s not hot is like going to a steakhouse and not getting meat. </em><br />
—Angelo Womack, Roberta&#8217;s</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 5</strong><br />
<em>It has to be a little bit smokey. If it&#8217;s not smokey, it&#8217;s not really chili.</em><br />
—Josh Sharkey, Bark Hot Dogs</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rules #6<br />
</strong><em>Find the right balance by choosing a range of spicy, smoky and sweet chilies; that&#8217;s essential to layering flavor.<br />
</em>—Nathan Foot, Northern Spy Food Co. <em></em></p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 7</strong><br />
<em>Don&#8217;t undercook your beans. You can&#8217;t have good chili with raw beans. </em><br />
—Priscilla Yeh, Dresler, Dumont,  Dumont Burger</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 8</strong><br />
<em>Dark Beer and Coca-Cola. They act as a sweetener and a thickener. </em><br />
—Yesenia Santibanez, Carino</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 9</strong><br />
<em>It&#8217;s gotta have tequila. </em><br />
—Chis Young, The Commodore</p>
<p><strong>Ultimate Chili Rule # 10</strong><br />
<em>Low and slow.<br />
</em>—Jay Brooks, TV Food Network Test Kitchen<br />
<strong><br />
Ultimate Chili Rule # 11</strong><br />
<em>Cook it 2 days ahead—maybe 3. But definitely let it sit. It gets better the longer it sits, for sure.</em><br />
—Joel Javier, Telepan</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-1593" href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili/2011/02/03/crowd2/"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1593" title="Crowd2" src="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/files/2011/02/Crowd2.jpg" alt="" width="620" height="380" /></a></p>
<p>The concourse at Chelsea Market brimmed with chili lovers flitting from station to station as live bluegrass and country music played in the background.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-1594" href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili/2011/02/03/jimmy43/"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1594" title="Jimmy43" src="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/files/2011/02/Jimmy43.jpg" alt="" width="620" height="380" /></a></p>
<p>Jimmy Carbone, owner and operator of the East Village gastropub <a href="http://www.jimmysno43.com/">Jimmy&#8217;s No. 23</a>, doles out his team&#8217;s creation, a well-balanced, traditional chili.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-1595" href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili/2011/02/03/stirring/"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1595" title="Stirring" src="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/files/2011/02/Stirring.jpg" alt="" width="620" height="380" /></a></p>
<p>A cook from <a href="http://www.robertaspizza.com/" target="_blank">Roberta&#8217;s</a>, a popular Brooklyn pizza joint, uses his ladle to give the restaurant&#8217;s hearty, beef chunk-filled chili a vigorous stir.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-1596" href="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/the-11-ultimate-rules-of-chili/2011/02/03/serving/"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1596" title="Serving" src="http://blogs.menshealth.com/guy-gourmet/files/2011/02/Serving.jpg" alt="" width="620" height="380" /></a></p>
<p>Besides for sponsoring the event, Brooklyn Brewery also sponsored a team from the <a href="http://www.thefoodexperiments.com/" target="_blank">The Food Experiments</a>. Above, Nick Suarez and Theo Peck serve up bowls of their robust and aptly-named &#8220;Kitchen Sink&#8221; chili. Each bowl came topped with a fried jalapeno chip and a white bean puree.</p>
<p><strong>Make Northern Spy Food Co.&#8217;s festival-winning chili!<br />
</strong></p>
<p>While some teams were extremely secretive about what went into their chilies, Northern Spy Food Co. was nice enough to share their winning chili recipe with us. Just make sure you&#8217;re sitting down when you take your first bite.</p>
<p><strong>Texas Style Beer Braised Chili<br />
Chef: Nathan Foot</strong></p>
<p><strong>What You&#8217;ll Need:</strong><br />
10 dried Aji Panca peppers*<br />
10 dried Cascabel peppers*<br />
1 dried Habanero pepper*<br />
5 lbs ground chuck<br />
2 onions, diced<br />
4 dried red bell peppers, diced<br />
3 dried jalapenos, seeds removed &amp; diced<br />
2 bottles beer, a strong American ale or porter<br />
3 cups red wine<br />
2 each 28 oz cans peeled Italian tomatoes, crushed by hand<br />
1 Tbsp Ground Aleppo pepper*<br />
½ tsp cinnamon<br />
1 tsp ground cumin<br />
1 tsp cayenne (more if you’d like it spicier)<br />
3 tsp red chili flake<br />
1 head garlic, roasted<br />
1 small can pickled jalapenos, diced<br />
Salt and pepper<br />
1 bunch scallions, thinly sliced</p>
<p>Serves 8-10</p>
<p><strong>For the chili powder:</strong><br />
Toast the Aji Panca, cascabel, and habanero chilies in a 350 degree oven until they are fragrant and crunchy. Let them cool, then break them open and remove the seeds. Grind them in a spice grinder and set aside.</p>
<p><strong>For the chili:</strong><br />
Brown beef in a large stockpot over medium high heat. Drain off fat and remove beef from pot. Add the onion, red bell pepper, raw jalapenos, and ¼ cup of the chili powder to the pot. Cook until the vegetables are softened and the chili powder is toasted.  Deglaze with beer and red wine. Reduce by half and then add the tomatoes, Aleppo, cinnamon, cumin, cayenne and red chili flake. Simmer for at least an hour. Add beef back to the mix. Add roasted garlic, pickled jalapenos, and salt and pepper to taste. For spicier chili, add more Aleppo and cayenne. Garnish with scallions.</p>
<p>*These peppers can be found at Kalustyan’s or at most specialty/gourmet grocery stores.&nbsp;<div class="cf5_rps"><div class="rps_sldrtitle">Related Posts</div><div class="rps_wrapper">
